    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.35b.6"/>
                
                632 putman 
                <unclear/>
                <figure/> University of Arkansas 
                <hi rend="caps">FAYETTEVILLE</hi> 
                72701
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Friday, July 16, 1971</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Being an ardent fan of the Dick Cavett Show, I was very curious to see his ninety-minute interview with you broadcast last spring. I must tell you it was one of the most interesting programs I've seen and hope it will be repeated soon and often.</p> 
               
                <p>It was because of this show that I became interested in your writings, and recently I was able to find a copy of <hi rend="underline">Black Elk Speaks</hi> at a local bookstore. I've never before been so moved by a book as to even think about writing its author, but this was such a fascinating work that I can only wish for words to express how much I enjoyed it. When I finished reading it yesterday morning at 3 <hi rend="caps">A.M.</hi>, tears were running down my chee<unclear>ks</unclear><add><note>cheeks</note></add> for the loss of a great culture that existed in this country for centuries before the coming of the Western Man and his so-called "civilization", and that exists today only in dreams and legends and books such as yo<unclear>urs.</unclear><add><note>yours</note></add></p> 
                
                <p>Thank you for saving the life and wisdom of Black Elk for those of us t<unclear>oo</unclear><add><note>too</note></add> young to have known men like him and what they lived for. If there were only a hundred John Neihardts, there would be <unclear/><add><note>no</note></add> generation gap today.</p>
                I look forward to reading your other works and sharing them with my friend yours, 
                <fw type="curatorial">6</fw>
                
                    <salute>With deep respect
                        and humble affecti<unclear>ion</unclear></salute>
                tim Bikin 
                
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
